## T-A1.3: Builder eDSL — typed instruction emitter + Db/Dw + pseudo-ops

**Target crate**: `gbf-asm`
**Target file(s)**: `gbf-asm/src/builder.rs`
**Reference**: `planv0.md` §"Assembly eDSL" (line 2046), engineering rule 1 ("All generated executable code originates from `AsmIR` / `Instr` / audited runtime builders, never from ad hoc byte pushes"), engineering rule 10 (`Raw(Vec<u8>)` is an escape hatch, never the default).

### Background

The builder is the API surface that runtime code (F-A5) and compiler-generated code (Epic B) use to emit `AsmIR`. It must be ergonomic enough that runtime authors don't reach for `Raw` and tight enough that the typed invariants from T-A1.1 / T-A1.2 are preserved.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
pub struct Builder {
    section: Section,
    cur_provenance: InstrProvenance,
}

impl Builder {
    pub fn new(role: SectionRole, name: SymbolName) -> Self;
    pub fn emit(&mut self, instr: Instr);
    pub fn db(&mut self, byte: u8);
    pub fn dw(&mut self, word: u16);
    pub fn label(&mut self, name: SymbolName) -> SymbolId;
    pub fn align(&mut self, align: u16);
    pub fn raw(&mut self, bytes: Vec<u8>);              // ESCAPE HATCH — emits a clippy lint
    pub fn with_provenance<R>(&mut self, p: InstrProvenance, f: impl FnOnce(&mut Self) -> R) -> R;

